    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-04-25T17:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-04-25T17:15:00-05:00" n="220"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d220">
                <head>220. Memorandum of a Conversation Between the <gloss type="from"
                        >President</gloss> and the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>,
                    Washington, April 25, 1955, 5:15 p.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d220fn1"
                        >Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library,
                            <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> Papers, Meetings with the
                        President. Secret; Personal and Private. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1955-04-25T17:15:00-05:00"
                            >April 25, 1955, 5:15 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I brought to the President the four-part message from <persName corresp="#p_RWS1"
                        >Walter Robertson</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d220fn2">
                        <ref target="#d219">
                            <hi rend="italic">
                                <ref target="#d220">Supra</ref>
                            </hi>
                        </ref>.</note> I told him that in essence the reaction of the <persName
                        corresp="#p_CKG1">Generalissimo</persName> was negative to the proposals
                    that have been put up to him. The President said that he was sorry that
                        <persName corresp="#p_RAAW1">Radford</persName> did not find any merit in
                    the “outpost” theory and said that he himself had never expected that the
                        <persName corresp="#p_CKG1">Generalissimo</persName> would give up outright
                    on Quemoy and the Matsus.</p>
                <p>I referred to the statement made by <persName corresp="#p_CE1">Chou
                        En-lai</persName> at Bandung and the State Department statement which had
                    been issued on Saturday. I said I thought that we should be prepared to indicate
                    receptivity to any “cease fire” proposal and that our Asian friends at Bandung
                    who had brought about the apparently more pacific mood on the part of the
                    Chinese Communists would expect this of us. The President agreed that I should
                    take this line at my press conference on Tuesday.<note n="3" xml:id="d220fn3"
                        >April 26.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion concerning the proposed Bricker Amendment to the
                    Constitution.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">JFD</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
